Let's denote the number of left-handed boys by $g$. Since there are  twice as many left-handed girl students as there are left-handed students, we get that the number iof left-handed students is just $2g$. Furthermore, we know that the number of right-handed boys is four times as many as the number of left-handed boys, thus it is just $4g$. Next, half of all the girls are left-handed. This means that the number of girls is just twice as many as the number of left-handed girls, which gives us
\begin{equation*}
  \left[ 2g \right] + 2\cdot [ 2g ] = 3g  = 36
\end{equation*}
so that there are $36/3 = 12$ girls. The number of left handed girls is then just
\begin{equation*}
   2g = 24  \text{ and the number of right handed girls is then just} 12-  24  = 18. 
\end{equation*}
Let's add the number of right-handed boys to the number of right-handed girls and get the number of right-handed people. We arrive at $4g + 18 = 48 +18 = 66$.


